                            .card-header(id="faq-heading2-02")
                                h5.mb-0
                                    button.btn.btn-link.btn-block.text-left.d-flex(type="button", data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#faq-collapse2-02", aria-expanded="false", aria-controls="faq-collapse2-02", style="white-space:normal !important; word-wrap: break-word") Why shouldn't I just store my data on a Hooli Box?
                                        img.p-1.ml-auto.my-auto(src="placeholder/icons/chevron-circle-down.svg", alt="")
                            .collapse(id="faq-collapse2-02", aria-labelledby="faq-heading2-02", data-parent="#faq-02")
                                .card-body.border-bottom  That's just the thing - if you store your data in a single place, like Gavin Belsons' poorly-made server box, your data will very susceptible to hacking. Whereas on PiperNet, your data is safe with many copies to back it up from.
                        .card.mb-2
                            .card-header(id="faq-heading3-02")
                                h5.mb-0
                                    button.btn.btn-link.btn-block.text-left.d-flex(type="button", data-toggle="collapse", data-target="#faq-collapse3-02", aria-expanded="false", aria-controls="faq-collapse3-02", style="white-space:normal !important; word-wrap: break-word") What makes PiperNet so safe?
                                        img.p-1.ml-auto.my-auto(src="placeholder/icons/chevron-circle-down.svg", alt="")
                            .collapse(id="faq-collapse3-02", aria-labelledby="faq-heading3-02", data-parent="#faq-02")
                                .card-body.border-bottom  Our proprietary middle-out compression algorithm allows data to flow so fast that it can't be hacked! But, in all seriousness, the algorithm helps but it's the public, immutable ledger that makes it secure. This enables PiperNet users to exchange data without risk of it being intercepted by third parties.
